<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920110-0099</DOCNO><DOCID>920110-0099.</DOCID><HL>   New Jersey Regulators   Plan Closer Scrutiny   Of Casino Finances</HL><DATE>01/10/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>CASINOS AND GAMBLING (CNO)ENTERTAINMENT AND LEISURE (ENT)</IN><RE>NEW JERSEY (NJ)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   ATLANTIC CITY -- New Jersey's Casino Control Commissionsaid it is going to pay more attention to casinos' financialability to help fund redevelopment of Atlantic City.   &quot;Casino gambling was legalized as a mechanism to rebuildAtlantic City,&quot; said Steven Perskie, chairman of thecommission. &quot;It won't be accomplished by companies withhighly leveraged balance sheets that can't afford to makeinvestments in Atlantic City's future.&quot;</LP><TEXT>   The Commission announced plans for a public hearing Feb. 3on new standards to measure financial stability of casinolicensees. The rules would give casino officials and others abetter guide to required financial standards; in the past,financial stability issues have been judged on a case-by-casebasis.   Consultants who prepared the new criteria said all 12casinos operating in Atlantic City are financially stableunder the proposed definition. But some &quot;could still findthemselves facing serious -- and unacceptable -- financialproblems,&quot; Mr. Perskie said.   New Jersey's Casino Reinvestment Act requires casinos toinvest the equivalent of 1.25% of gross gaming revenue indevelopment authority bonds or in projects approved by theauthority.</TEXT></DOC>